{"@context":"http://iiif.io/api/presentation/3/context.json","id":"https://tintaliquida.github.io/narratingwaterscapes/manifests/interview-with-panamanian-historian-francisco-javier-bonilla.json","type":"Manifest","label":{"en":["Interview with Panamanian Historian Francisco Javier Bonilla"]},"homepage":[{"id":"https://tintaliquida.github.io/narratingwaterscapes","type":"Text","label":{"en":["Interview with Panamanian Historian Francisco Javier Bonilla"]},"format":"text/html"}],"metadata":[{"label":{"en":["Description"]},"value":{"en":["Dr. Francisco Javier Bonilla is a historian of Latin America specializing in environmental history, infrastructure, and urban development. His research focuses on Panama and the wider Caribbean, examining how water, cities, and U.S. empire have shaped everyday life across the region. He received his PhD in History from Carnegie Mellon University and is currently turning his dissertation, Downstream from the Locks: The Technopolitics of Water in Panama’s Urban Borderlands, into a book. In this interview with Bill Miller, he addresses the Río Indio project and what it means for Panama."]}},{"label":{"en":["Language"]},"value":{"en":["English"]}}],"items":[{"id":"https://tintaliquida.github.io/narratingwaterscapes/interview_with_panamanian_historian_francisco_javier_bonilla/canvas/1","type":"Canvas","duration":0,"annotations":[{"@context":"http://iiif.io/api/presentation/3/context.json","id":"https://tintaliquida.github.io/narratingwaterscapes/manifests/interview_with_panamanian_historian_francisco_javier_bonilla-canvas1-1","type":"AnnotationPage","label":{"en":["Default"]},"items":[{"@context":"http://www.w3.org/ns/anno.jsonld","type":"Annotation","motivation":["commenting","tagging"],"id":"https://tintaliquida.github.io/narratingwaterscapes/interview_with_panamanian_historian_francisco_javier_bonilla/canvas/1/page1","body":[{"type":"TextualBody","value":"Here, Dr. Bonilla addresses the cross-ownership of media, political campaigns, and mega-corporations, proving how the state/corporate alliance maps and controls public discourse.","format":"text/plain","motivation":"commenting"},{"type":"TextualBody","value":"state-mapping","format":"text/plain","purpose":"tagging","motivation":"tagging"},{"type":"TextualBody","value":"exclusion","format":"text/plain","purpose":"tagging","motivation":"tagging"}],"target":"https://tintaliquida.github.io/narratingwaterscapes/interview_with_panamanian_historian_francisco_javier_bonilla/canvas/1#t=935,980"},{"@context":"http://www.w3.org/ns/anno.jsonld","type":"Annotation","motivation":["commenting","tagging"],"id":"https://tintaliquida.github.io/narratingwaterscapes/interview_with_panamanian_historian_francisco_javier_bonilla/canvas/1/page1","body":[{"type":"TextualBody","value":"He highlights the physical expansion of the logistical state. Infrastructure projects alter geography by moving beyond traditional watershed boundaries.","format":"text/plain","motivation":"commenting"},{"type":"TextualBody","value":"dam","format":"text/plain","purpose":"tagging","motivation":"tagging"},{"type":"TextualBody","value":"reservoir","format":"text/plain","purpose":"tagging","motivation":"tagging"},{"type":"TextualBody","value":"state mapping","format":"text/plain","purpose":"tagging","motivation":"tagging"}],"target":"https://tintaliquida.github.io/narratingwaterscapes/interview_with_panamanian_historian_francisco_javier_bonilla/canvas/1#t=981,1019"},{"@context":"http://www.w3.org/ns/anno.jsonld","type":"Annotation","motivation":["commenting","tagging"],"id":"https://tintaliquida.github.io/narratingwaterscapes/interview_with_panamanian_historian_francisco_javier_bonilla/canvas/1/page1","body":[{"type":"TextualBody","value":"This part of the interview makes us think about how a \"lived territory\" is reduced to an extraction zone, resulting in displacement and forced relocation. At the same time, it reveals how the media censors structural alternatives to the Canal's infinite growth model. This testimony serves as a critical point of view against that status quo.","format":"text/plain","motivation":"commenting"},{"type":"TextualBody","value":"lived territory","format":"text/plain","purpose":"tagging","motivation":"tagging"},{"type":"TextualBody","value":"exclusion","format":"text/plain","purpose":"tagging","motivation":"tagging"},{"type":"TextualBody","value":"testimony","format":"text/plain","purpose":"tagging","motivation":"tagging"},{"type":"TextualBody","value":"counter mapping","format":"text/plain","purpose":"tagging","motivation":"tagging"},{"type":"TextualBody","value":"grassroots","format":"text/plain","purpose":"tagging","motivation":"tagging"}],"target":"https://tintaliquida.github.io/narratingwaterscapes/interview_with_panamanian_historian_francisco_javier_bonilla/canvas/1#t=1026,1069"}]}],"items":[{"id":"https://tintaliquida.github.io/narratingwaterscapes/interview_with_panamanian_historian_francisco_javier_bonilla-canvas1/paintings","type":"AnnotationPage","items":[{"id":"https://tintaliquida.github.io/narratingwaterscapes/interview_with_panamanian_historian_francisco_javier_bonilla-canvas1/paintings","type":"Annotation","motivation":"painting","body":{"id":"https://youtu.be/pIxLEnMykz0?si=e6WgXwtBnFGRjL0R","type":"Video","format":"unknown","duration":0},"target":"https://tintaliquida.github.io/narratingwaterscapes/interview_with_panamanian_historian_francisco_javier_bonilla/canvas/1"}]}]}]}